        <h2 id="examples">Real content gap analysis examples</h2>
        <h3>1. HVAC company — 25 first-page rankings in 4 months</h3>
        <p>An HVAC contractor ran a gap analysis against 4 regional competitors. Output: 40+ untapped furnace and AC maintenance keywords. They published 15 articles over one quarter and earned 25 first-page rankings within 4 months.</p>
        <h3>2. SaaS company — 30% of demos from comparison content</h3>
        <p>A SaaS team found 200+ comparison keywords ("[competitor] vs [competitor]", "[competitor] alternatives") that competitors covered but they ignored. They built out versus pages over 6 months. Result: <strong>30% of inbound demo requests</strong> now come from that comparison hub.</p>
        <h3>3. B2B agency — filling format gaps</h3>
        <p>An agency's gap analysis surfaced that competitors ranked with calculators and templates, not just blog posts. Adding 6 free tools captured 40+ high-intent commercial keywords within 5 months.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Content gap analysis vs keyword research — how they differ</h2>
        <p>Both surface keyword opportunities. The lens is different.</p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content gap analysis</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Starts from competitor rankings</li>
              <li>Only surfaces keywords proven to drive traffic</li>
              <li>Prioritizes by competitor overlap</li>
              <li>Best for building or expanding a strategy</li>
              <li>Output is a prioritized production list</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/keyword-research/">Keyword research</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Starts from seed keywords or topics</li>
              <li>Surfaces all queries with volume, ranked or not</li>
              <li>Prioritizes by volume and difficulty</li>
              <li>Best for exploring new categories</li>
              <li>Output is a broader keyword universe</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 content gap analysis best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Choose actual SERP competitors, not brand competitors.</strong> The site outranking you may not be the brand you compete with in sales.</li>
          <li><strong>Filter by keyword difficulty relative to your DR.</strong> A domain with DR 20 chasing DR 70 keywords wastes cycles.</li>
          <li><strong>Weight by intent, not just volume.</strong> A 200/mo commercial keyword beats a 2,000/mo informational one for most B2B sites.</li>
          <li><strong>Cluster before you assign.</strong> Group 5 to 15 related gaps into a single pillar + supporting article set.</li>
          <li><strong>Compare formats too.</strong> If competitors rank with tools, calculators, or video — note it. Format gaps close revenue faster than blog gaps.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh before you write new.</strong> Fixing an existing underperforming page often beats publishing a brand-new one.</li>
          <li><strong>Rerun quarterly.</strong> Competitors publish. Google shifts. A stale gap list produces stale content plans.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — targeting gaps you cannot win</div>
          <p>A gap you cannot win is not an opportunity. If the SERP is dominated by domains with DR 80+ and yours is DR 25, that "gap" is a mirage. Filter aggressively by <a href="/glossary/keyword-difficulty/">keyword difficulty</a> or you will spend a year publishing to page 4.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content gap analysis mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Analyzing too many competitors.</strong> More than 5 produces noise. Stick to 3 to 5 actual SERP rivals.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring intent.</strong> A gap with high volume but no purchase intent produces traffic without leads.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the topic-cluster step.</strong> Publishing 40 disconnected gap articles builds no topical authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Failing to update internal links.</strong> New gap articles need <a href="/glossary/internal-link/">internal links</a> from existing pages to rank.</li>
          <li><strong>Running the analysis once.</strong> A gap analysis is a system, not an event. Rerun every 90 days.</li>
        </ul>

